ce:section.ce:para:
The interference of the system to DPA monitoring in the presence of various interfering biological ions, aromatic carboxylic acid and amino acids (1 μM) was measured, and the anti-interference and selectivity of CDs@SiO2-Tb were investigated. The interfering amino acids include glutamic (Glu), D-phenylalanine (Phe), D-aspartic (Asp), glycine (Gly), DL-methionine (Met), and Tryptophan (Trp). Aromatic carboxylic acids have o-phthalic (o-PA), m-phthalic (m-PA), and benzoic (BA) acids. Norfloxacin(Nor), ciprofloxacin(Cip), 2,3-pyridine dicarboxylic acid (2,3-DPA) and 2,5-pyridine dicarboxylic acid (2,5-DPA) are also be considered. With the introduction of DPA, the fluorescence intensity ratio increased obviously, but the fluorescence changes caused by other interferents can be ignored (Fig. 7
                        ). The CDs@SiO2-Tb has good selectivity for DPA detection may be due to the unique molecular structure of DPA, which has two carboxyl groups alone with the nitrogen atom of pyridine, providing stronger interactions with Tb3+ through metal–ligand chelation coordination and ion-pairing interaction [40]. Moreover, the triplet state energy of DPA matches the resonant emission energy of Tb3+, which is conducive to the energy transfer from DPA to Tb3+ 
                        [26]. Therefore, DPA-induced fluorescence sensitization has high specific recognition.
